'''Jevargi''' ([[Kannada]]:ಜೇವರ್ಗಿ) is a [[panchayat town]] in [[Gulbarga district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Karnataka]]. It is also the headquarters of the Jevargi Taluk.

==Geography==
Jevargi is located at {{coor d|17.02|N|76.77|E|}}<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/19/Jevargi.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Jevargi]</ref>. It has an average elevation of 393&nbsp;[[metre]]s (1289&nbsp;[[foot (unit of length)|feet]]). The town is spread over an area of 4.25 sq. km. <ref name="area"> The area of major towns in Karnataka has been mentioned in the webpage [http://municipaladmn.kar.nic.in/AreapopE.htm Population of Corporation/CMC/TMC/TP]belonging to the Municipal Administration Department of the Government of [[Karnataka]]</ref>

Jevargi Taluk borders [[Afzalpur]] Taluk of [[Gulbarga district]] and [[Gulbarga]] Taluk of [[Gulbarga district]] to the north, [[Chitapur]] Taluk of [[Gulbarga district]] to the east, [[Shahpur]] Taluk of [[Gulbarga district]] to the south-east, [[Shorapur]] Taluk of [[Gulbarga district]] to the south and [[Sindgi]] Taluk of [[Bijapur]] district to the west.

[[Bhima]] river flows near Jevargi.

==Demographics==
[[As of 2001]] India [[census]]{{GR|India}}, Jevargi had a population of 19,174. Males constitute 51% of the population and females 49%. Jevargi has an average literacy rate of 53%, lower than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 63%, and female literacy is 43%. In Jevargi, 17% of the population is under 6 years of age.

==Places to see==
* Aralgundagi in Jewargi Taluk is the birth place of Lord Sharanabasaveshwara and is famous for the Rathotsava (Chariot festival) held there.
* Jevargi has lots of Jain temples and is an important pilgrimage centre for [[Jains]].

